en","fullItemName":"Scenario: Delayed walking in children"},{"id":"f63a11de-e155-5afe-a226-402d885f4423","slug":"limp-in-children","fullItemName":"Scenario: Limp in children"},{"id":"da28c3e0-278d-5fce-8968-bdc734d3e305","slug":"out-toeing","fullItemName":"Scenario: Out-toeing"},{"id":"3130a07e-303c-5b73-838c-5d6307fdead8","slug":"tip-toe-walking","fullItemName":"Scenario: Tip toe walking"}]},{"id":"086fd10d-b722-534e-b18d-5a0a2d5792c9","fullItemName":"Supporting evidence","slug":"supporting-evidence","subChapters":[]},{"id":"bf424233-1954-55a8-98de-834693dbdd11","fullItemName":"How this topic was developed","slug":"how-this-topic-was-developed","subChapters":[{"id":"6728c56f-47a6-56f1-be0e-22c22275d9e9","slug":"search-strategy","fullItemName":"Search strategy"},{"id":"2d75ec25-86dd-542a-b968-a3f7e80d0210","slug":"stakeholder-engagement","fullItemName":"Stakeholder engagement"},{"id":"2514c9ed-51af-51be-8f7d-3a997605efe6","slug":"evidence-exclusion-criteria","fullItemName":"Evidence exclusion criteria"},{"id":"6bdf3ba0-4bec-595d-bb71-c68f7fcb7c9c","slug":"organizational-behavioural-financial-barriers","fullItemName":"Organizational, behavioural and financial barriers"},{"id":"20bd862c-7ca7-5a5b-8f5d-443cd0bea04c","slug":"declarations-of-interest","fullItemName":"Declarations of interest"}]},{"id":"b747cefd-4366-540b-87c3-72fdbb926a30","fullItemName":"References","slug":"references","subChapters":[]}]},"parentChapter":{"id":"8d402bd6-6ff7-597f-8744-fe50598828b1","slug":"management","fullItemName":"Management"},"subChapters":[{"id":"b35e25a0-057d-58e3-a49c-50016e9d5ceb","slug":"bow-legs","fullItemName":"Bow legs","depth":3,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 7700bca5-57bc-48e6-94ef-aa0600b69633 --><h3>When should I consider referring a child with bow legs?</h3><!-- end field 7700bca5-57bc-48e6-94ef-aa0600b69633 -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 3c47028a-d2ce-4aca-8898-aa0600b69633 --><!-- begin field 11de3c13-9227-4cf5-ae2f-aa0600b69633 --><ul><li><strong>Management in the community (for example by a physiotherapist with paediatric expertise) is usually appropriate for a child with bow legs if <em>all </em>the following are present:</strong><ul><li>Well with no <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/diagnosis/assessment-for-red-flags/\">red flags</a>.  </li><li>Aged less than 4 years.</li><li>Not in pain.</li><li>Not functionally impaired (play, walking, milestones normal).</li><li>Growing and developing normally.</li></ul></li><li><strong>Consider referring children with bow legs for specialist assessment, using clinical judgement to determine the urgency, if <em>any</em> of the following are present: </strong><ul><li>A <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/diagnosis/assessment-for-red-flags/\">red flag</a> feature.</li><li>Bow legs in a child older than 4 years<strong>.</strong></li><li>Bow legs at any age with an acute deformity at the proximal tibia (possible Blount's disease). </li><li>Severe deformity<strong> </strong>or<strong> </strong>femoral intercondylar distance more than 6 cm.</li><li>Unilateral or asymmetrical findings. </li><li>Pain.</li><li>Limp. </li><li>Joint swelling or abnormal joint examination.</li><li>Functional impairment, such as recurrent trips and falls and mobility problems.<strong> </strong></li><li>Regression or delayed motor milestones.</li><li>Concern about rickets, metabolic or endocrine disorders,<strong> </strong>dysplasia or dysmorphism. </li><li>Short stature or disproportionate growth (for example limbs are short compared to the trunk). </li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 11de3c13-9227-4cf5-ae2f-aa0600b69633 --><!-- end item 3c47028a-d2ce-4aca-8898-aa0600b69633 -->","subChapters":[{"id":"fd41d5e7-7674-5456-9aff-54030a75d44a","slug":"basis-for-recommendation-e89","fullItemName":"Basis for recommendation","depth":4,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field f1a32a97-0740-4b6d-97b7-aa0e01018319 --><h4>Basis for recommendation</h4><!-- end field f1a32a97-0740-4b6d-97b7-aa0e01018319 -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item e894355a-28a1-4afa-9e95-aa0e010182c6 --><!-- begin field 6dbd77bd-167d-4f02-99dc-aa0e01018319 --><h4>Community management</h4><ul><li>The recommendation on when community management is usually appropriate is based on musculoskeletal triage guidance for children and young people [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">RightPath, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">RightPath, 2019</a>]. <strong> </strong><ul><li>For most children with bow legs, no treatment is required because the deformity resolves over time [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Mooney, 2014</a>]. Experts recommend reassuring parents that bow legs usually resolve spontaneously by 4 years of age and that nonsurgical interventions (for example bracing, special shoes, and inserts) are not usually indicated [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Mooney, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Rerucha et al, 2017</a>]. </li></ul></li></ul><h4>Referral</h4><ul><li>The recommendation on when to consider referral is based on musculoskeletal triage guidance for children and young people [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">RightPath, 2017</a>], an explanation of the pGALS (paediatric Gait, Arms, Legs, and Spine) examination [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Foster, 2013</a>], and expert opinion in review articles [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Mooney, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Yeo et al, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Evans, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Rerucha et al, 2017</a>].  <ul><li>In a small number of children, bracing or surgical intervention may be indicated (for example infantile Blount disease, skeletal dysplasia, bony manifestation of endocrine or renal abnormalities) [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Mooney, 2014</a>]. There may be an association with pathologic bow legs and early osteoarthritis. Surgery may be necessary if the condition does not spontaneously resolve or there is extreme angulation [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/developmental-rheumatology-in-children/references/\">Rerucha et al, 2017</a>].  </li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 6dbd77bd-167d-4f02-99dc-aa0e01018319 --><!-- end item e894355a-28a1-4afa-9e95-aa0e010182c6 -->","subChapters":[]}]}]}}},"staticQueryHashes":["3666801979"]}